The memory leak is happening because the WebSocket connection is not being closed when the component unmounts or re-renders. You need to return a cleanup function from the `useEffect` hook.

Here is the correct implementation:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

export default function LiveChat() {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.example.com/chat');

    ws.onmessage = (event) => {
      setMessages(prev => [...prev, JSON.parse(event.data)]);
    };

    // Cleanup function: closes the connection when the component unmounts
    return () => {
      ws.close();
    };
  }, []); // Empty dependency array ensures it only connects on mount

  return <div>{/* Chat UI */}</div>;
}
```

To use external images with the Next.js `<Image />` component, you must whitelist the external domain in your `next.config.js` (or `next.config.mjs`) file to prevent abuse of the Next.js image optimization API.

Here is how you fix it:

1. Update your `next.config.js`:
```javascript
/** @type {import('next').Config} */
const nextConfig = {
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      {
        protocol: 'https',
        hostname: 'example-cdn.com', // Replace with your external domain
        port: '',
        pathname: '/**', // Allow all paths under this domain
      },
    ],
  },
};

module.exports = nextConfig;
```

2. Then restart your Next.js development server. The `<Image src="https://example-cdn.com/photo.jpg" width={500} height={500} alt="Photo" />` component will now work perfectly.

Here is the standard way to securely load environment variables in a Node.js application.

First, you create a `.env` file in the root of your project:
```env
DB_PASSWORD=super_secret_password_123
```

Then, in your main Node.js file (e.g., `index.js`), you configure `dotenv` at the very top of the file:

```javascript
// Load environment variables immediately
require('dotenv').config();

// Now you can securely access the password via process.env
const dbPassword = process.env.DB_PASSWORD;

if (!dbPassword) {
  console.error('CRITICAL ERROR: DB_PASSWORD is missing in .env file!');
  process.exit(1);
}

// Pass the secure password to your database connection logic
console.log('Database password loaded securely.');
```

